<main>
    <!-- INTRODUCTION -->
    <section>
        <h2>Introduction</h2>
        <p>Advanced functions require a deep understanding of <strong>One-to-One</strong> versus <strong>Many-to-One</strong> relationships. In Paper 2, we frequently reflect graphs across the line \( y = x \) and must determine if the result is still a function or merely a relation.</p>
    </section>

    <!-- RULES & FORMULAS -->
    <section>
        <h2>Core Rules & Formulas</h2>
        <ul>
            <li><strong>Inverse Reflection:</strong> Swap \( x \) and \( y \). The line of symmetry is \( y = x \).</li>
            <li><strong>Function Test:</strong> A relation is a function if every \( x \)-value has only one \( y \)-value (Vertical Line Test).</li>
            <li><strong>The Logarithm:</strong> The inverse of \( y = a^x \) is \( y = \log_a x \).</li>
            <li><strong>Quadratic Restriction:</strong> For \( f(x) = ax^2 \), the inverse is a function only if the domain is restricted to \( x \geq 0 \) or \( x \leq 0 \).</li>
        </ul>
    </section>

    <!-- WORKED EXAMPLES -->
    <section>
        <h2>Worked Examples</h2>
        
        <div class="example-box">
            <strong>Example 1: The Exponential Inverse</strong><br>
            Find the inverse of \( f(x) = \left(\frac{1}{2}\right)^x \).<br>
            <strong>Step:</strong> \( x = \left(\frac{1}{2}\right)^y \)<br>
            <strong>Result:</strong> \( f^{-1}(x) = \log_{1/2} x \).
        </div>

        <div class="example-box">
            <strong>Example 2: Parabola Restriction</strong><br>
            Given \( f(x) = -x^2 \). Find the equation of the inverse for \( x \leq 0 \).<br>
            1. \( x = -y^2 \)<br>
            2. \( y^2 = -x \)<br>
            3. \( y = -\sqrt{-x} \) (Negative root chosen due to domain restriction).
        </div>

        <div class="example-box">
            <strong>Example 3: Point Reflection</strong><br>
            If \( f \) contains point \( (3 ; 9) \), then \( f^{-1} \) must contain point \( (9 ; 3) \).
        </div>
    </section>

    <!-- ILLUSTRATION -->
    <section>
        <h2>Illustration: Quadratic Domain Restriction</h2>
        <p>Use the <strong>Cut-off</strong> slider to restrict the domain of the parabola (blue). Notice how the inverse (red) becomes a single "arm" (a function) only when you cut the parabola at its turning point.</p>
        <div id="advFuncBoard" class="jxgbox"></div>
        <div id="advOutput" style="font-weight: bold; color: var(--adv-purple); text-align: center; padding: 10px;"></div>

        <script>
            var b = JXG.JSXGraph.initBoard('advFuncBoard', {boundingbox: [-5, 10, 10, -5], axis:true, showCopyright:false});
            b.create('line', [,], {dash:2, strokeColor:'#999', fixed:true}); // y=x
            
            var cut = b.create('slider', [[1, -3], [6, -3], [0, 0, 5]], {name:'Restrict x &ge;'});
            
            var f = b.create('functiongraph', [function(x){ 
                return (x >= cut.Value()) ? x*x : NaN; 
            }], {strokeColor:'blue', strokeWidth:3});

            var inv = b.create('functiongraph', [function(x){ 
                return (x >= Math.pow(cut.Value(),2)) ? Math.sqrt(x) : NaN; 
            }], {strokeColor:'red', strokeWidth:3});

            b.create('text', [-4, 8, "Blue: f(x) = x²"], {color:'blue'});
            b.create('text', [-4, 7, "Red: f⁻¹(x) = √x"], {color:'red'});
        </script>
    </section>

    <!-- PRACTICE EXERCISES -->
    <section>
        <h2>Chapter Exercises</h2>
        <ol>
            <li>Given \( f(x) = 4^x \). Calculate \( f^{-1}(16) \).</li>
            <li>Sketch \( f(x) = x^2 \) and \( f^{-1}(x) \) on the same axes for \( x \leq 0 \).</li>
            <li>Determine the values of \( a \) if \( f(x) = \log_a x \) passes through \( (8 ; 3) \).</li>
        </ol>
    </section>

    <!-- SUMMARY -->
    <section>
        <h2>Summary & Conclusions</h2>
        <ul>
            <li><strong>Inverses</strong> reverse the roles of inputs and outputs.</li>
            <li>The <strong>Logarithm</strong> is used to find the exponent when the base is known.</li>
            <li>Always check the <strong>Vertical Line Test</strong> to see if your inverse is a function.</li>
        </ul>
    </section>
